        </profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-04-30T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-04-30T18:00:00-05:00" n="716" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d716">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00B/4–648: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-04-30T19:00:00-04:00">April 30, 1948—7 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>652. Does Emb think reconsideration of question retaining consular offices in
                    cities threatened by Communist occupation (particularly <pb facs="0823" n="813" xml:id="pg_813"/> Mukden) warranted in light possibility increased anti-US
                    feeling arising from China aid program as reported Shanghai’s tel. 933 Apr
                        27<note n="11" xml:id="d716fn11">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_209">p. 209</ref>.</note> and
                    Communist attitude toward foreigners reported Mukden’s tel. 198 Mar 30<note n="12" xml:id="d716fn12">Not printed.</note> to you?</p>
                <p>Although Dept aware Communist attitude toward retention consular offices
                    described in Hong Kong’s memo Mar 9<note n="13" xml:id="d716fn13">Not printed,
                        but for summary see <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note> forwarded with
                    Embdes 164 Apr 6<note n="14" xml:id="d716fn14">See footnote 7, <ref target="#pg_812">p. 812</ref>.</note> may well differ from that of
                    Communist leaders, it believes contents this memo would be of interest to Mukden
                    and possibly other consular offices north China, If Emb has not already done so,
                    it should communicate pertinent portions this memo to those offices.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
